\documentclass[11pt]{article}\usepackage{aahomework}\usepackage{mathtools}% \usepackage{subcaption}\usepackage{epstopdf}\usepackage{float}\usepackage{% xcolor}\usepackage{parskip}	ikzstyle{blk}=[circle,innersep=0pt,minimumsize=4% pt,draw,fill=black,linewidth=0.8pt]	ikzstyle{blanknode}=[circle,innersep=3pt,% minimumsize=8pt,draw,linewidth=0.8pt]	ikzstyle{blk}=[circle,innersep=0pt,% minimumsize=4pt,draw,fill=black,linewidth=0.8pt]\par \geometry{letterpaper,% textwidth=17cm,textheight=22cm}\par \usetikzlibrary{arrows}\usetikzlibrary{% plotmarks}\par \par \par \par  egin{document} \par \@@section{section}{Sx1}{}{}{}{Recall} \par  egin{enumerate} \enumerate@item{ Row-echelon form } \enumerate@item{ Reduced row echelon form (rref) } \enumerate@item{ Row operations  egin{enumerate} \enumerate@item{ Multiply a row by a scalar: ${\color{black} oxed@math{{\color{black}cR_{i}}}}% $ } \enumerate@item{ Swap rows: ${\color{black} oxed@math{{\color{black}R_{i}\circlearrowright R_{% j}}}}$ } \enumerate@item{ Add a multiple of one row to another: ${\color{black} oxed@math{{\color{black% }R_{i}+cR_{j}}}}$ } \end{enumerate} } \end{enumerate} \par It is important to note that a matrix can have many row-echelon forms --% row echelon form is not unique. It is only the \emph{reduced} row echelon % form that is unique. \par Let us take a look at an example. Consider the system \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left. egin{aligned}\displaystyle x+3y&\displaystyle% =4\ \displaystyle 5x-4y&\displaystyle=-7\end{aligned}ight\}$ First, we represent this system as an augmented matrix. Our goal then is to % perform row operations to achieve one of two forms \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&3&4\ 5&-4&-7\end{matrix}ight]\longrightarrow\underbrace{\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r% ]1&0&*\ 0&1&*\end{matrix}ight]	ext{ or }\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&0&*\ 0&0&1\end{matrix}ight]}_{	ext{rref.}}$ After we achieve one of these forms, we can determine much of the information % that we want to know about the system. \par \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&3&4\ 5&-4&-7\end{matrix}ight]\ \xrightarrow[]{-5R_{1}+R_{2}}\ \left[ egin{matrix% }[rr|r]1&3&4\ 0&-19&-27\end{matrix}ight]\ \xrightarrow[]{- rac{1}{19}R_{2}}\ \left[ egin% {matrix}[rr|r]1&3&4\ 0&1& rac{27}{19}\end{matrix}ight]$ \par Both of these matrices are in echelon form. If we want to find the % reduced row echelon form of the matrix, then we still need to eliminate non-% zero entries in the columns above leading non-zero entries: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&3&4\ 0&1& rac{27}{19}\end{matrix}ight]\ \xrightarrow[]{-3R_{2}+R_{1}}\ % \underbrace{\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&0& rac{-5}{19}\ 0&1& rac{27}{19}\end{matrix}ight]}_{	ext{rref.}}$ We have now obtained the reduced row echelon form of the augmented matrix. Our% goal was to solve the original system. We can see how the reduced row echelon% form helps us find the solution by converting it back into a system: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&0& rac{-5}{19}\ 0&1& rac{27}{19}\end{matrix}ight]\longrightarrow\left\{ egin{aligned}% \displaystyle x&&&\displaystyle= rac{-5}{19}\ &&\displaystyle y&\displaystyle= rac{27}{19}\end{aligned}ight.$ We see that the solution to the system comes very easily from the reduced row % echelon form. \par The leading non-zero entries in the echelon and reduced row echelon form% matrices were very important in this process. We can now introduce some new % terminology. \par  egin{itemize} \itemize@item{ A {pivot entry} is the leading non-zero entry in a matrix in echelon form. Non% -pivot entries are simply those entries that are not pivot entries. } \itemize@item{ A {pivot column} or basic column is the column containing a pivot entry. } \itemize@item{ A {free column} is a column that does not contain pivot entries. } \end{itemize} \par Looking back at the previous example, \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]{\color{red} oxed@math{{% \color{black}1}}}&3&4\ 0&{\color{red} oxed@math{{\color{black}1}}}& rac{27}{19}\end{matrix}ight]$ We find the matrix has two pivot entries (red), and so this matrix has two % pivot columns and one free column. \par \par These ideas have meaning in the sense of variables as well.  egin{itemize} \itemize@item{ A {pivot variable} is a variable of the system corresponding to a pivot column% . } \itemize@item{ A {free variable} is a a variable corresponding to a free column. } \end{itemize} One obvious but important fact is that the sum of the pivot and non-pivot % variables equals the total number of variables in the system. \par If we consider the previous example, we find there are two pivot % variables and no free variables: \par \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rr|r]1&0& rac{-5}{19}\ 0&1& rac{27}{19}\end{matrix}ight]$ \par With this terminology in mind, let us address the question of whether we% can predict the number of solutions a system will have. \par Suppose we have some system that we reduce to this form. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle	ext{System}\longrightarrow\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|% r]1&0&0&2\ 0&0&0&3\ 0&0&1&1\end{matrix}ight]$ Examining this matrix, we find it has three pivot entries: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|r]{\color{red} oxed@math{{% \color{black}1}}}&0&0&2\ 0&0&0&{\color{red} oxed@math{{\color{black}3}}}\ 0&0&{\color{red} oxed@math{{\color{black}1}}}&1\end{matrix}ight]$ This then tells us that  egin{itemize} \itemize@item{ There are two pivot entries, which are both $1$. } \itemize@item{ There are two pivot columns: the first and third. } \itemize@item{ There are two free columns: the second and fourth. } \end{itemize} To address which variables are free and which are pivots, we need to associate% a variable with each column. Suppose the variables of the first, second, and % third columns are, respectively, $x,y,z$.  egin{itemize} \itemize@item{ There are two pivot variables: $x$ and $y$. } \itemize@item{ There is one free variable: $y$. } \end{itemize} \par In presenting this problem, note that we were not actually given a % matrix in echelon form. The reason the matrix does not qualify as echelon is % due to the fact that there are non-zero entries in the third row that are not % to the right of the leading non-zero entry in the second row. \par To fix this, we need to perform additional row operations. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|r]1&0&0&2\ 0&0&0&3\ 0&0&1&1\end{matrix}ight]\xrightarrow[]{R_{2}\circlearrowright R_{3}}\left[%  egin{matrix}[rrr|r]1&0&0&2\ 0&0&1&1\ 0&0&0&3\end{matrix}ight]$ The matrix is now in echelon form. \par Let us reassess this matrix. First, it is in echelon form but not rref % due to the fact that the leading non-zero entry in the third row is a $3$. The% pivot entries are now different: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|r]{\color{red} oxed@math{{% \color{black}1}}}&0&0&2\ 0&0&{\color{red} oxed@math{{\color{black}1}}}&1\ 0&0&0&{\color{red} oxed@math{{\color{black}3}}}\end{matrix}ight]$  egin{itemize} \itemize@item{ Pivots: $1,1,3$ } \itemize@item{ Pivot columns: $1,3,4$ } \itemize@item{ Free columns: $2$ } \itemize@item{ Pivot variables: $x,z$ } \itemize@item{ Free variables: $y$ } \end{itemize} \par Let us convert this matrix into a system of equations: \par \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[rrr|r]1&0&0&2\ 0&0&1&1\ 0&0&0&3\end{matrix}ight]\longrightarrow\left\{ egin{aligned}\displaystyle x% &&&&&\displaystyle=2\ &&&&\displaystyle z&\displaystyle=1\ &&&&\displaystyle 0&\displaystyle=3\end{aligned}ight.$ Observe that this tells us that $x=2$, $z=1$ and $y$ can be anything. However,% observe that it also says that $0=3$. \par Because the system of equations says that $0=3$, the system can have no % solution. This is thus an example of an \emph{inconsistent} system, as we have% discussed previously. \par This suggests that we might be able to tell when this will occur by % looking at the echelon form matrix. Thinking about it, it is apparent that % whenever a pivot is in the constant vector column, the resulting system will % have such an inconsistent equation. \par \par Succinctly, \par \@add@centering ramebox[][r]{ \centering egin{minipage}[t]{0.0pt} Suppose we have a system, represented by an augmented matrix \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[c|c]A&\vec{b}\end{matrix}ight]% $ which we reduce it to \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[c|c]R&\vec{c}\end{matrix}ight]% $ where $R$ is echelon or rref. of $A$ and this reduction results in $\vec{b}	o% \vec{c}$. \par If the right side column of $\left[ egin{matrix}[c|c]R&\vec{c}\end{% matrix}ight]$ has a pivot, then the system is inconsistent. \end{minipage} } \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx1.SS0.SSS0.Px1}{}{}{}{Question:}Is the converse % also true? That is, that if a system is inconsistent, that a pivot must be % present in the constant column? \par The answer to this will come later. \par It seems that pivot and free variables determine the nature of the % system. Let us consider another example system: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left[ egin{matrix}[cccc|c]1&2&3&4&0\ 0&0&2&1&2\ 0&0&0&7&5\end{matrix}ight]$ We'll assign variables to the columns: $x,y,z,w$ for columns $1$ through $4$, % respectively.  egin{enumerate} \enumerate@item{ Pivot columns: 1,3,4 } \enumerate@item{ Free columns: 2,5 } \enumerate@item{ Pivot variables: $x,z,w$ } \enumerate@item{ Free variables: $y$ } \end{enumerate} \par The first question we probably want to answer is: is the system % consistent or inconsistent? Let us convert the augmented matrix back into a % system: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{aligned}\displaystyle x+2y+3z+4w&\displaystyle% =0\ \displaystyle 2z+w&\displaystyle=2\ \displaystyle 7w&\displaystyle=5\end{aligned}$ From here, it is apparent that we can use the third equation to obtain a value% for $w$. We can then plug this value into the second equation to obtain a % value for $z$. Plugging these two into the first equation, we might think we % can then obtain the value of $x$. But, remember that $y$ is a free variable. % After isolating the values of $w$ and $z$, we should then be able to pick any % value of $y$ and be able to find the value of $x$ that satisfies the values of% $w,z,$ and $y$. This tells us that the system is consistent. \par Let us actually solve the system. The last line gives us that $w=5/7$. % Then from the second equation, \@@amsalign$\displaystyle 2z+w$&$\displaystyle=2$\ $\displaystyle z$&$\displaystyle= rac{2-w}{2}= rac{2- rac{5}{7}}{2}= rac{9% }{14}$ Next, we can use these two values in the first equation to obtain \@@amsalign$\displaystyle x+2y+3z+4w$&$\displaystyle=0$\ $\displaystyle x$&$\displaystyle=-2y-3z-4w$\ $$&$\displaystyle=-2y- rac{27}{14}- rac{20}{7}$\ $$&$\displaystyle=-2y- rac{47}{14}$ We haven't selected any value for $y$ yet, even though since it is a free % variable we should be able to pick any value we want for it. For example, we % can select $y=0$ and then we simply have that $x=-47/14$. If we pick $y=-2$, % we obtain $y=-2-(47/14)=-75/14$. \par We find that for every $y\in bR$ we pick, there is a $x$ corresponding % to it. Hence the system is consistent. Additionally, we have found much more % than just that the system is consistent, we have in fact found that it will % have infinitely many solutions. \par \par Having a free variable makes it \emph{possible} for the system to % have infinitely many solutions. We just need to be careful that the system has% any solutions at all; \emph{there could be an inconsistent system that still % has free variables}. In that case, there would still be no solutions to the % system. \par Otherwise, it is the case that for a consistent system, having a free % variable means it will have infinitely many solutions. \par It still remains to be seen what determines whether there will be a % unique solution to a system. \par Before we move on, let us discuss how to write the solution to a system.% We have found the solution to a system already, but there is a more % convenient way to present such a solution, called the {vector form} of a % solution. \par \par Looking at the previous example, we will first write the variables % of the system in a column vector \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x\ y\ z\ w\end{bmatrix}$&$\displaystyle=$ \par We isolated specific values for $w$ and $z$. Since $y$ is free we will % simply write $y=y$, and we will write the expression for $x$ that depends on $% y$. Since $y$ is free it is good practice to write the choice of $y$; in this % case, $y$ can be any real number ($y\in bR$). \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x\ y\ z\ w\end{bmatrix}$&$\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}-2y- rac{47}{14}\ y\  rac{9}{14}\  rac{5}{7}\end{bmatrix}\qquad,y\in bR$ We will always present the \emph{solution set} in this form. \par Next, let us try writing the solution in a slightly different manner: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x\ y\ z\ w\end{bmatrix}$&$\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix} rac{-47}{14}\ 0\  rac{9}{14}\  rac{5}{7}\end{bmatrix}+y egin{bmatrix}-2\ 1\ 0\ 0\end{bmatrix}\qquad,y\in bR$ There are some benefits of splitting the solution in this way. First, this % form indicates that the solution, in four dimensions, is actually a line. We % can interpret this by considering a lower-dimensional case. \par  egin{figure}[H] \centering	ikzpicture \clip(-.5,-.5) to (-.5, 5) to (8,4) to (8,-.5); \draw[->,>=triangle 60,thick] (0,-1) to (0,4); \draw[->,>=triangle 60,thick] (-1,0) to (5,0); \par \draw(-.5,3.3750) to (5,-.75); 
ode[blk] (particular) at (4,0) {}; \draw[->,>=triangle 60,line width=2pt] (4,0) to (2,1.5); \par 
ode(pointlabel) at (5.5,1) {Particular point}; 
ode(veclabel) at (3.5,2.5) {Vector along line}; \par \draw[->,>=triangle 60,line width=1pt] (pointlabel) to (particular.north % east); \par \draw[->,>=triangle 60,line width=1pt] (veclabel) to (3,1); \@add@centering\end{figure} \par In two dimensions, a line is determined by any particular point on the % line, and the vector that lies along the line. Back in the current example, % the first vector represents the particular point, whereas the second is the % vector lying along the line. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}x\ y\ z\ w\end{bmatrix}$&$\displaystyle=\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix} rac{-47}{14}\ 0\  rac{9}{14}\  rac{5}{7}\end{bmatrix}}_{\mathclap{	ext{Particular point on the line}}}+y% \overbrace{ egin{bmatrix}-2\ 1\ 0\ 0\end{bmatrix}}^{\mathclap{	ext{Vector along the line}}}\qquad,y\in bR$ \par This may be familiar to those who have taken differential equations. The% particular point is analogous to the particular solution, whereas the vector % part of the solution is the homogeneous solution. \par \end{document}

